{"id":"2007.08425","submitter":"Patrick Schelling","authors":"Kevin Fernando and Patrick K. Schelling","title":"Non-local linear-response functions for thermal transport computed with\n  equilibrium molecular-dynamics simulation","comments":"Changes:: Title has changed. Previous assumptions about the\n  denominator in Eq. 22 were incorrect. These are now found by MD simulation.\n  The response functions are slightly changed as result. Figures 8-10 are\n  changed. Time-dependence of the source is explained in Appendix A. More\n  references were included to justify the approach used to derive Eq. 22","journal-ref":"Journal of Applied Physics 128, 215105 (2020)","doi":"10.1063/5.0032014","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We establish an approach to compute linear-response functions to elucidate\nheat waves and non-local thermal transport. The theory is able to describe the\nresponse of a system to external heat sources that are nonuniform in space and\ntime. The response functions are computed using equilibrium molecular-dynamics\nsimulations of an Ar crystal modeled using the standard Lennard-Jones\npotential. It is shown that for low temperatures and short length scales,\ntransport can be partially or even completely ballistic, with the response\nprimarily limited by the group velocity of lattice waves. By contrast, at\nlonger length scales and higher temperatures, the response functions correspond\nmore closely to diffusive transport characteristic of Fourier's law. It is also\nshown how the effective thermal conductivity can be determined in a\npartially-ballistic regime. The results demonstrate the known reduction in the\neffective thermal conductivity observed when system dimensions are smaller than\nthe mean-free path for lattice waves. Finally, we show how determination of the\nrelevant response functions can be used to model heating of a crystal without\nrequiring additional atomic-scale simulations. Differences between computed\nresults and predictions from Fourier's law represent wave-like,\npartially-ballistic transport.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 16 Jul 2020 16:05:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 30 Sep 2020 18:16:50 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 3 Nov 2021 01:46:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-04"}
